{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:163","names":{"en":"Sultans of Gujarat","tr":"Gücerat Sultanları","ar":"Salātīn Gujarāt"},"country":["AF","BD","IN","PK"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":null},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"163","atlas_name_en_original":"The Sultans of Gujarat","parent_tribe":"Muzafferî ailesi (Tânk Râcpût dönmesi)","ethnic_origin":"Hindistanlı Müslüman (Râcpût dönme)","capital":"Ahmedabad","region_primary":"Gücerat","regions_all":"Ahmedabad; Cambay; Surat; Gücerat","geographic_zone":"Güney Asya","predecessor":"Delhi Sultanlığı valileri","successor":"Bâbürlü Ekber ilhakı","government_type":"Sultanlık|Şahlık","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Sultans of Gujarat established a powerful Islamic state centered on Ahmedabad on India's western coast, shaped by maritime trade and Portuguese rivalry. Ahmedabad's architectural legacy forms the most lasting trace of this era.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"23.02","capital_lon":"72.57","century_start":14,"century_end":16}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:162","names":{"en":"Sultans of Kashmir","tr":"Keşmir Sultanları","ar":"Salātīn Kashmīr"},"country":["AF","BD","IN","PK"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":null},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"162","atlas_name_en_original":"The Sultans of Kashmir","parent_tribe":"Şâh Mîr Svâtî ailesi; Çek ailesi","ethnic_origin":"Keşmirli Müslüman","capital":"Srînagar","region_primary":"Keşmir","regions_all":"Srînagar; Keşmir vadisi","geographic_zone":"Güney Asya","predecessor":"Hindu Keşmir kralları","successor":"Bâbürlü Ekber ilhakı (c. 994/1586)","government_type":"Sultanlık","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Sultans of Kashmir were a dynasty forming a distinctive branch of Islamic civilization in the sheltered Himalayan valley. Sultan Zayn al-'Ābidīn created Kashmir's golden age through his tolerance policy between Hindus and Muslims. The Kashmir shawl and handicraft traditions took root in this period.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"34.09","capital_lon":"74.79","century_start":14,"century_end":16}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:180","names":{"en":"Abdālī","tr":"Afganistan Dürrânî ve Bârekzây Hükümdarları","ar":"al-Durrāniyyūn wa-al-Bārakzā'iyyūn"},"country":["AF","IN"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1747,"extinct":1973},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"180","atlas_name_en_original":"The Abdālī or Durrānī Rulers and Kings of Afghanistan","parent_tribe":"1. Sâdûzay/Pôpâlzay (Abdâlî/Dürrânî); 2. Bârekzây/Muhamedzây","ethnic_origin":"Afgan (Peştun)","capital":"Kandahar → Kâbil","region_primary":"Afganistan","regions_all":"Kandahar; Kâbil; Herât; Peşâver; Keşmir (geçici); Pencap (geçici)","geographic_zone":"Güney Asya","predecessor":"Afşar/Safevî yönetimi","successor":"Afganistan Cumhuriyeti (1973 Dâvûd Han darbesi)","government_type":"Şahlık","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Durrānī and Bārakzay rulers represent modern Afghanistan, founded by Aḥmad Shāh Durrānī. While Aḥmad Shāh is regarded as the 'father of Afghanistan,' the Bārakzay period was shaped by three Anglo-Afghan Wars. Afghanistan's buffer state identity formed during this era.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"34.53","capital_lon":"69.17","century_start":18,"century_end":20}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:159","names":{"en":"Ghūrid","tr":"Gurlular (Gûrîler)","ar":"al-Ghūriyyūn"},"country":["AF","IN"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":1215},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"159","atlas_name_en_original":"The Ghūrids","parent_tribe":"Şensebânî/Gûr Tâcik ailesi","ethnic_origin":"İranî (Tâcik)","capital":"Fîrûzkûh; Gazne","region_primary":"Afganistan ve Kuzey Hindistan","regions_all":"Gûr (Fîrûzkûh); Gazne; Lahor; Delhi; Bâmiyân; Tohâristân; Bedehşân","geographic_zone":"Güney Asya","predecessor":"Gazneliler","successor":"Delhi Sultanlığı (Hindistan); Hârezmşah fethi (Horasan)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Ghūrids were an Iranian dynasty emerging from Afghanistan's mountainous Ghur region, ensuring Islam's permanent entry into India. Mu'izz al-Dīn's victory at the Battle of Tarain (1192) opened northern India to the Islamic world, while they left masterpieces like the Minaret of Jam.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"33.55","capital_lon":"68.42","century_start":10,"century_end":13}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:175","names":{"en":"Mughal Emperor","tr":"Bâbürlüler (Moğol İmparatorları)","ar":"al-Mughaliyyūn / al-Bāburiyyūn"},"country":["AF","IN"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1526,"extinct":1858},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"175","atlas_name_en_original":"The Mughal Emperors","parent_tribe":"Timurlu-Cengiz soyu (Barlas)","ethnic_origin":"Türk-Moğol (Timurlu)","capital":"Agra; Delhi; Fetihpûr Sikrî (geçici); Şâhcihânâbâd (Delhi)","region_primary":"Hindistan alt kıtası","regions_all":"Delhi; Agra; Lahor; Dekkan; Bengal; Keşmir; Kâbil","geographic_zone":"Güney Asya","predecessor":"Delhi Sultanlığı (Lodîler)","successor":"İngiliz Hindistanı (1858)","government_type":"Şahlık","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Mughals built the most magnificent period of Islamic civilization in the Indian subcontinent on the Timurid legacy, establishing one of world history's wealthiest empires. Beginning with Babur's victory at Panipat (1526), the dynasty institutionalized the Hindu-Muslim synthesis through Akbar's unique tolerance policy (Sulh-i Kul). The Shah Jahan era reached the pinnacle of Islamic architecture with the construction of the Taj Mahal, while Aurangzeb extended the empire to its widest borders but accelerated centrifugal forces. Mughal court culture — miniature painting, garden tradition, the birth of Urdu — permanently shaped South Asia's cultural identity. The dynasty, reduced to a shadow empire by the increasing intervention of the British East India Company, ended with the exile of the last emperor Bahadur Shah Zafar after the 1857 Rebellion.","importance_level":"Kritik","capital_lat":"28.61","capital_lon":"77.21","century_start":16,"century_end":19}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:158","names":{"en":"Ghaznawid","tr":"Gazneliler","ar":"al-Ghaznawiyyūn"},"country":["AF","IN","IR"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":977,"extinct":1186},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"158","atlas_name_en_original":"The Ghaznawids","parent_tribe":"Türk gulâm ailesi","ethnic_origin":"Türk","capital":"Gazne → Lahor","region_primary":"Afganistan ve Kuzey Hindistan","regions_all":"Gazne; Lahor; Horasan (erken); Pencap","geographic_zone":"Güney Asya","predecessor":"Sâmânî gulâm valileri","successor":"Gurlular (Lahor'u aldı 582/1186)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":"Sünnî","narrative_en":"The Ghaznavids were a Turkic dynasty that gained independence from Samanid ghulam governorship, establishing a powerful empire from Afghanistan to northern India. Sultan Mahmud launched seventeen campaigns into India, initiating the first great wave of Islam's spread in the subcontinent. Patronizing Ferdowsi's Shahnameh and hosting universal scholars like Bīrūnī, Mahmud is one of Islamic history's most contradictory rulers.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"33.55","capital_lon":"68.42","century_start":10,"century_end":12}}
